Annotations in Java 5+ are present to introduce semantics. We often add to that some kind of behavior (for example, in JUnit, the @Test annotation runs a new test case which fails or succeeds or fails). But I was wondering if it was possible to add an @Example annotation that has no behavior associated with it. Yes, an annotation that has the retention RetentionPolicy.SOURCE; I would see it being associable to ElementType.METHOD and TYPE.

But what would it mean? Well the @Example annotation would be exactly what it means: it shows that the current method is an example of how to use the code snippet that is written in the method below. This is therefore useful to write typical usage code.

But why this annotation in JUnit? Well, I think the answer is obvious, but some might say otherwise, so here I go. JUnit is extremely often used in snippets all over the internet to show how code should be written with a particular API. This code itself is very often written in the "test" source folder because people don't want to really create a "usage" source folder: it's not exactly what people are taught. In order to "enforce" that code should be written like that, often typical JUnit's Assert are used, and if we would simply add a @Test annotation to the method, it would pass without any issue.

The thing is that JUnit, by the absence of such an annotation, recommends to not use any annotation for these test cases, or possibly use @Ignored. This is not really explicit in this use case: people already use JUnit to create sample methods. This is only an adaptation of JUnit to the common usage.

Here's how I would write such an annotation:

@Retention(SOURCE)
@Target({METHOD, TYPE})
public @interface Example {
  Class<? extends Exception> expected();
}

When using @RunWith(Parametrized.class), test names are shown as methodName[fParameterSetNumber], but it would be very useful to see the actual parameter values (so they will be visible in the IDE and other test runners).

The only way I found is to completely overwrite Parametrized class and change implementation of the following methods in inner class TestClassRunnerForParameters:

    @Override
    protected String getName() {
      return String.format("[%s]%s", fParameterSetNumber, Arrays.asList(fParameterList.get(fParameterSetNumber)));
    }

    @Override
    protected String testName(final FrameworkMethod method) {
      return String.format("%s[%s]%s", method.getName(),
          fParameterSetNumber, Arrays.asList(fParameterList.get(fParameterSetNumber)));
    }

It would be really handy if Parametrized runner did that out of the box or had an option to do that.

